\section{Learning objective}
The objectives of this experiment are to provide the student with an opportunity to:

\begin{itemize}
\item Become more familiar using Matlab for data acquisition, analysis, and dissemination (plotting, etc.).
\item Design, build, and test a non-inverting amplifier circuit using a generic operational amplifier chip.
\item Design, build, and test an instrumentation amplifier circuit using an instrumentation amplifier chip.
\item Explore and verify the performance characteristics of operational amplifiers.
\item Verify the gains of the constructed op-amp circuits.
\end{itemize}

\section{Equipment checklist}

\begin{itemize}
\item LM358AN Op-Amp
\item AD622AN Instrumentation Amp
\item Digilent Breadboard
\item Powered Breadboard (or similar power supply)
\item Wire \& Resistor Kits
\item Screw Driver, Pliers, Wire Stripper
\item NI MyDAQ
\item Analog Input (AI) and Analog Output (AO) on MyDAQ
\end{itemize}

\section{Introduction}
In this experiment you will construct and test two op-amp circuits. The first will be the non-inverting amplifier shown in Figure 1, using National Instruments’ LM358 DIP (dual in-line package) chip. The second will be an instrumentation amplifier circuit using Analog Device’s AD622 DIP. Both circuits will have a gain of approximately G = 3.  Details for both of these DIP chips are given at the end of this document.

\section{Laboratory instruction}
The goal of this experiment is to learn about operational amplifier and setting up the gain in the op-amp circuit.
\section{Part-A: Construct and test a non-inverting amplifier}
\begin{itemize}
\item Fabricate a non-inverting amplifier on a breadboard. Select resistors from the supply kit at your station.
\item Select R1= 10 k$\Omega$ and R2 =20 k$\Omega$ resistors from your resistor kit. Verify the correct color bands using a resistor chart (or internet resource), then measure and record the actual resistor values using the tabletop DMM in order to calculate the expected gain.
\item Reference the LM358 datasheet for how to connect the DIP chip.
\item Place the op-amp in the bread board across the center channel as seen in Figure \ref{fig:opAmp}.
\item Construct your circuit on the breadboard in a neat and organized manner. Use pre-bent wires when possible; trim wires so that they are tight to the breadboard. Use the long vertical rails for your common signals (such as the +15V, -15V, ground, etc.). Your lab assistant may ask you to organize your wiring before helping you to debug your circuit.
\item Use the NI MyDAQ power supply to provide +15V and -15V to the chip at the V+ and GND pins respectively (note – the GND pin on the LM358 amplifier is not the signal ground, it should be -15V for this experiment).
\item Use the ground from the Digilent breadboard to ground the op-amp circuit.
\item Connect your resistors as shown in Figure \ref{fig:opAmp}, with R1 = 10 k$\Omega$ and R2 = 20 k$\Omega$.
\item Use the Analog Out (AO 0) on the NI MyDAQ for supplying the input voltage to your op-amp circuit (use a range of 0-5 Volts for input). This will be done in the Acquisition code provided for this experiment (see line 33 - 36 in the provided Matlab code for acquisition)
\item Use the handheld digital multi-meter to test the non-inverting op-amp circuit to verify that it is performing correctly.
\item Sample breadboard circuit is shown in Figure \ref{fig:opAmp}. Few things to note in the circuit. The wiring provided is color coded for clarity
\begin{itemize}
\item Yellow color wires: are  ground 
\item Blue color wires: are $V^{-}_{supply}$ negative supply voltage
\item Red color wires: are $V^{+}_{supply}$ negative supply voltage
\item Green color wire: are $V_{out}$ output voltage signal, , Acquired at AI-0 of NI MyDAQ
\item Orange color wire: are $V_{in}$, input voltage signal, generated from AO-0 of NI MyDAQ and then Acquired at AI-1 of NI MyDAQ to record the data.
\end{itemize}
\item Show your circuit to TAs before acquiring the data. {\bf Wrong wire will damage the op-amp}.
\item After the acquisition is done and data is recorded, {\bf please use DMM to record input voltage and output voltage to the LM358 circuit in your log book}. \emph{For check : The input voltage value should be close to 5 volts. The output voltage should be greater than 10 volts}.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=4.5in]{LM358CircuitNew.png}
\caption{Sample wiring diagram for LM358 op-amp.}
\label{fig:opAmp}
\end{figure}

\section{Part-B: Create a Matlab Program to Acquire and Display Data from the NI MyDAQ.}
You will the a generic acquisition program to collect the input to Op-Amp and output voltage from Op-Amp, see the sample code in the appendix \ref{app:mainDAQProgram}.
\begin{itemize}
\item Make sure to set the sampling rate to 200 Hz and sampling to to 5 seconds. 
\item Make sure to acquire data on two channels of DAQ system. AI0 will be used for output signal from op-amp and AI1 will be used to acquire input voltage to op-amp.
\item Make sure the output filename is correct before starting the acquisition program. Line 21 in the Matlab code.
\item The program should gradually increase to 5 volts from 0 volts. This is done on the Analog output terminal ``0'', it generates the input signal to the op-amp circuit. This will be done in the Acquisition code provided for this experiment (see line 33 - 36 in the provided Matlab code for acquisition)
\item The acquisition program should acquire the data and store it in a file. Make sure the relative file path is correct.
\item For this part of the experiment the filename should be ``LM358Data.dat''
\item After the acquisition is done and data is recorded, {\bf please use DMM to record input voltage and output voltage to the LM358 circuit in your log book}. \emph{For check : The input voltage value should be close to 5 volts. The output voltage should be greater than 10 volts}.
\item Why the recorded output voltage in log book is different than the output voltage shown in your DAQ plot? 
\end{itemize}

\section{Part-C: Connect and test an instrumentation amplifier}
\begin{itemize}
\item Use the other side of the breadboard to build the circuit for AD622 chip.
\item Construct an instrumentation amplifier with a gain of G = 3 on the breadboard.  Select resistors from the supply provided at your station. The gain for the AD622 is set with an external resistor (use the datasheet link given at the end of this document as reference).
\item Measure and record the actual resistor values.
\item Construct your circuit on the breadboard in a neat and organized manner. Use pre-bent wires when possible; trim wires so that they are tight to the breadboard. Use the long vertical rails for your common signals (such as the +15V, -15V, ground, etc). If necessary, your lab assistant may ask you to organize your wiring before helping you to debug your circuit.
\item Use the NI MyDAQ power on breadboard to provide +15V and -15V to the chip at the V+ and V- pins respectively.
\item Use the ground from the Digilent breadboard to ground the circuit and the output ground from the op-amp circuit, as well as the REF pin on the instrumentation amplifier (this acts as signal ground).  
\item Use the Analog Out (AO 0) on the NI MyDAQ for supplying the input voltage to your op-amp circuit (use a range of 0-5 Volts for input). This will be done in the Acquisition code provided for this experiment (see line 33 - 36 in the provided Matlab code for acquisition)
\item Use the handheld digital multi-meter to test the non-inverting op-amp circuit to verify that it is performing correctly.
\item Sample breadboard circuit is shown in Figure \ref{fig:opAmp2}.
\item Show your circuit to TAs before switching on the power. {\bf Wrong wire will damage the instrumentation amplifier}.
\item Sample breadboard circuit is shown in Figure \ref{fig:opAmp}. Few things to note in the circuit. The wiring provided is color coded for clarity
\begin{itemize}
\item Yellow color wires: are  ground 
\item Blue color wires: are $V^{-}_{supply}$ negative supply voltage
\item Red color wires: are $V^{+}_{supply}$ negative supply voltage
\item Green color wire: are $V_{out}$ output voltage signal, , Acquired at AI-0 of NI MyDAQ
\item Orange color wire: are $V_{in}$, input voltage signal, generated from AO-0 of NI MyDAQ and then Acquired at AI-1 of NI MyDAQ to record the data.
\end{itemize}
\item Show your circuit to TAs before acquiring the data. {\bf Wrong wire will damage the op-amp}
\item After the acquisition is done and data is recorded, {\bf please use DMM to record input voltage and output voltage to the AD622 circuit in your log book}. \emph{For check : The input voltage value should be close to 5 volts. The output voltage should be greater than 10 volts}.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=6.0in]{AD622CircuitNew.png}
\caption{Sample wiring diagram for AD622 instrument amplifier.}
\label{fig:opAmp2}
\end{figure}

\section{Part-D: Create a Matlab Program to Acquire and Display Data from the NI MyDAQ. Code provided for this semester}
You will the a generic acquisition program to collect the input to Op-Amp and output voltage from Op-Amp, see the sample code in the appendix \ref{app:mainDAQProgram}.
\begin{itemize}
\item Make sure to set the sampling rate to 200 Hz and sampling to to 5 seconds. 
\item Make sure to acquire data on two channels of DAQ system. AI0 will be used for output signal from op-amp and AI1 will be used to acquire input voltage to AD622.
\item Make sure the output filename is correct before starting the acquisition program. Line 21 in the Matlab code.
\item The program should gradually increase the input signal voltage to 5 volts from 0 volts.  This is done on the Analog output terminal ``0'', it generates the input signal. This will be done in the Acquisition code provided for this experiment (see line 33 - 36 in the provided Matlab code for acquisition)
\item The acquisition program should acquire the data and store it in a file. Make sure the relative file path is correct.
\item For this part of the experiment the filename should be ``LM358Data.dat''
\item After the acquisition is done and data is recorded, {\bf please use DMM to record input voltage and output voltage to the AD622 circuit in your log book}. \emph{For check : The input voltage value should be close to 5 volts. The output voltage should be greater than 10 volts}.
\item Why the recorded output voltage in log book is different than the output voltage shown in your DAQ plot? 
\end{itemize}

